The effect of a physical exercise program in palliative care: A phase II study.

Oldervoll LM(1), Loge JH, Paltiel H, Asp MB, Vidvei U, Wiken AN, Hjermstad MJ, 
Kaasa S.

Author information:
(1)The Norwegian Cancer Society, Department of Cancer Research and Molecular 
Medicine, St. Olavs Hospital, Trondheim, Norway. line.oldervoll@ntnu.no

Comment in
    J Pain Symptom Manage. 2006 Dec;32(6):513-5; author reply 515-6.

The purpose of this pilot study was to assess the effects of a physical exercise 
program on physical performance and quality of life (QOL) in a population with 
incurable cancer and a short life expectancy. Thirty-four patients participated 
in a 50-minute group exercise program twice a week for 6 weeks. Physical 
performance was measured by three tests: "6-minute walk test," "timed repeated 
sit to stand," and "functional reach." Fatigue was measured by the Fatigue 
Questionnaire. QOL was assessed by the European Organization for Research and 
Treatment of Cancer Core Quality of Life Questionnaire. The outcome variables 
were assessed before and after the intervention. The walk length increased and 
the "timed repeated sit to stand" was reduced (P < 0.05). Emotional functioning 
improved and physical fatigue was reduced (P < 0.05). Physical exercise seems to 
be a feasible way to improve well-being among patients with incurable cancer. 
Future randomized trials are needed to confirm the results.

